library(rvest)

Problem 1.1 (Long-to-Wide Data format translation):

We demonstrated the wide-to-long conversion in lecture. Now, lets explore long-to-wide. Load in the long-format SOCR Parkinsons Disease data. and export it as wide format. For simplicity, just choose only 3 variables (avoiding case and time variables). Please note that there are several time observations for each subject. You need to transform the features according to the time variable. Try to use reshape function.

pd_data_5 = pd_data[, c("Cases", "Sex", "Weight", "Age", "Time")]
pd_data_5_wide = reshape(pd_data_5, idvar = c("Cases", "Sex", "Weight", "Age"), timevar = 'Time', direction = 'wide')
pd_data_5_wide[1:5, ] #show part of the result
##    Cases Sex Weight Age
## 1      2   1     84  67
## 5      3   0     97  39
## 9      6   0     96  54
## 13     7   1     79  53
## 17     8   1     79  46

Problem 1.3 (Simulation)

Generate 1,000 standard normal variables and 1,200 student t distributed random variables with df=20. Generate a quantile-quantile (Q-Q) probability plot of the two samples. Then, compare it with qqnorm of student t simulation.

The distribution of sampling student t data is much similar to the default normal data, comparing to the normal sampling one since the more dots at two tails are closer to qqline.

set.seed(7)
nd = rnorm(1000, mean=0, sd=1); sd = rt(1200, 20)
qqplot(nd, sd, pch = 20, col = 'blue', xlab = 'Sampling Quantiles of the N (Normal) Data', 
       ylab = 'Sampling Quantiles of the T (Student) Data', main = 'Normal v.s. Student T Q-Q Plot'); qqline(nd)

qqnorm(sd, pch = 20, col = 'blue', ylab = 'Sampling Quantiles of the T (Student) Data'); qqline(sd)

Problem 1.4 (Define an R SD function)

Generate a function that computes a sample standard deviation function and compare it against the sd function using the simulation data you generate in the last question.

fun_sd = function(d){
  sqrt(sum((d - mean(d))^2)/(length(d) - 1))
}
c(sd(nd), sd(sd))
## [1] 0.9823217 1.0636471
c(fun_sd(nd), fun_sd(sd))
## [1] 0.9823217 1.0636471
